{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module-to-client handoff (request builder + API client contract), not model judgment. An in-process fake client that captures outbound payload can catch missing/partial taxonomy lists. Rejected System because behavior text is about request contents, not real network/OS effects. Rejected Agentic because no dependence on model output quality.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module to a fake API client that records requests. Invoke classification with a known taxonomy and assert the outbound payload includes every valid label exactly once before send.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is response-handling across module boundaries (API adapter -> normalization/validation -> public return). A stubbed API returning an out-of-taxonomy label reproduces the real failure. Rejected Agentic because behavior text only requires handling an invalid returned string, not validating model decision quality. Rejected System because no real network behavior is required.","test_description":"Use a fake API response containing an invalid label (for example, \"medical\" when not in taxonomy). Assert module output is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior text targets deterministic normalization logic for identical input; no cross-module or I/O boundary is required. Rejected Integration because no handoff/state propagation is needed to expose this failure.","test_description":"Call the normalization function repeatedly with the same raw response fixture and assert identical normalized label each run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI API calls and consistency of returned labels, which depends on real model/provider output characteristics. A stub would hide this failure mode. Rejected Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification calls, not a multi-stage agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N live calls for identical document+taxonomy, capture raw provider responses and final labels, and assert label stability when raw response is unchanged; flag drift when labels vary without provider-response change.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at wiring boundary among tokenizer/budget policy/dispatcher. In-process integration with a fake sender is enough to verify pre-dispatch truncate/reject behavior. Rejected System because behavior text is explicitly \"before dispatch,\" so real network/OS is not required. Rejected Agentic because no dependence on model output content.","test_description":"Configure a small token budget, pass an over-budget document, and assert module applies policy (truncate or reject) and only dispatches compliant payload (or does not dispatch on reject).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Requires a real provider call and real provider-reported token usage; mocks can falsely pass and miss production over-budget behavior. Even with deterministic assertion, execution depends on live AI API processing. Rejected System as final choice because the core risk is provider/model-side usage behavior, not only transport/HTTP mechanics.","test_description":"Execute live classification for representative documents with configured budget, read provider usage metadata, and assert reported prompt/total tokens are within budget threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.66,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This tests retry orchestration (error handling, backoff, retry) around the API boundary; a deterministic fake API returning rate-limit then success can expose real logic bugs. Rejected System because real network timing is not required to validate wait-and-retry control flow. Rejected Agentic because correctness does not depend on model output quality.","test_description":"Use a fake API client scripted to return rate-limit response (e.g., 429/Retry-After) then success; assert module waits per policy, retries, and returns successful label i